article.headline: Air Force 64, IPFW 44
article.story: AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) -- Tim Keller scored 11 points and Air Force held Indiana-Purdue Fort Wayne without a field goal for a 14-minute span Friday night as the Falcons defeated IPFW 64-44. Air Force (9-2) improved on its nation-leading scoring defense, which entered the contest allowing 47.6 points a game, and won its seventh straight game for the first time since the 1972-73 season. Air Force held IPFW (2-13) to 15 points below its season average. It was IPFW's fifth straight loss. David Simon led IPFW with 19 points. Antoine Hood had 10 points for Air Force, eight of which came in the first half. Sophomore center Nick Welch turned in the most well-rounded performance of his career. Welch scored seven points, led the Falcons with five rebounds, made two steals, and had a career-high five assists. "He had given us toughness," Air Force coach Joe Scott said of the 6-foot-8 Welch. "Now, he's giving us the smarts to go with it in running the offense." Air Force made 9-of-12 field goals to start the game and pulled to a 29-12 lead midway through the first half. IPFW trailed 33-22 after a 3-pointer by Terry Collins with 6:55 left in the first half. It would be the last field goal for the Mastodons until Jim Kessenich's jumper with 12:49 to play made it 47-27 Air Force. The Falcons' smothering defense created an 18-9 turnover disparity and drew six offensive fouls against the Mastodons.
